## 1 Overview

In this lesson you are going to learn how to control a servo.

## 3 Components introduction

### Servomotor

A servomotor is an active component that is able of turning its arm precisely.
The servomotor included in the kit is able to turn from 0Ω resistor; degrees to 180Ω resistor; degrees. In
order to control its movement, you have to send it a PWM signal.

## 5 Code

Before running the script, do not forget to start the daemon for the **pigpio library** if you did not used this library after you started the terminal. You can start the daemon using **sudo pigpiod**.

The code starts by importing the libraries used, which are **pigpio** and **time**. We will create an instance for the previously imported library, which is **pigpio**, then declare the pin used by the servo and set it as an **OUTPUT**. Keep in mind that this library uses BCM numbering, so we will work with the **GPIO** version of the pins.

In the **while True** loop we will put the servo in the position of -90 degrees, 0 degrees and 90 degrees using the already implemented function from the pigpio library **set_servo_pulsewidth(pin, value)**, where pin is the pin used by the servo and **value** (pulsewidth) is a value between 500 and 2500. At the end of the code we will stop the servo using **pi.set_servo_pulsewidth(servo, 0)** and also the connection with the daemon.
